<sec id="sec-introduction">
  <title>1 Introduction</title>
  <p>Comparative Judgment often refers to the method of Comparative
  Judgement (DCJ,
  <xref alt="Thurstone 1927" rid="ref-Thurstone_1927" ref-type="bibr">Thurstone
  1927</xref>) where judges rate an object’s trait by means of pairwise
  comparisons in a dichotomous scale. Usually, in these types of
  experiments the objects are observational units from higher
  hierarchical levels, such as subjects. For example, when researchers
  are interested in assessing the trait of speech intelligibility of
  individuals (subjects), judges rate dichotomously two uttered
  sentences (objects, nested within individuals).</p>
  <p>DCJ have been successfully applied to education, e.g., for
  assessing writing quality van Daal
  (<xref alt="2020" rid="ref-vanDaal_2020" ref-type="bibr">2020</xref>),
  STEM abilities Bartholomew and Williams
  (<xref alt="2020" rid="ref-Bartholomew_et_al_2020" ref-type="bibr">2020</xref>),
  linguistics
  (<xref alt="Boonen, Kloots, and Gillis 2020" rid="ref-Boonen_et_al_2020" ref-type="bibr">Boonen,
  Kloots, and Gillis 2020</xref>). In marketing, e.g., recipe tasting
  such as in examples found in Lawson
  (<xref alt="2015" rid="ref-Lawson_2015" ref-type="bibr">2015</xref>).</p>
  <p>No CJ research have been submitted on the
  <italic>intersection</italic> of</p>
  <list list-type="order">
    <list-item>
      <p>Simulation-based power analysis</p>
      <p>importance for planning and reliability of results</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>For comparative judgments:</p>
      <p>sophisticated procedure to score traits:</p>
      <list list-type="bullet">
        <list-item>
          <p>between subjects</p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>against a reference subject</p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>to test research theories</p>
        </list-item>
        <list-item>
          <p>to test judges’ reliability</p>
        </list-item>
      </list>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Considering the predictability of the phenomena</p>
      <p>its importance in Shmueli and Koppius
      (<xref alt="2011" rid="ref-Shmueli_et_al_2011" ref-type="bibr">2011</xref>)
      and Lawson
      (<xref alt="2015, 7" rid="ref-Lawson_2015" ref-type="bibr">2015,
      7</xref>)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Under Bayesian framework</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Keeping a documentation of the implementation</p>
    </list-item>
  </list>
</sec>
